When you have measured out the amount of potassium hydroxide you will need for your batch of biodiesel, grab your funnel and place it on the container with the methanol. Make sure the amount of methanol you use is 20% to 22% of the original volume of your batch of oil. Pour in the potassium hydroxide and let it settle.Place the valve cap on the container of methanol. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/90/Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet1-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet1-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/90/Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet1-Version-2.jpg/v4-760px-Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet1-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

As the potassium hydroxide dissolves into the methanol, the mixture will heat up and boil. Bubbles will appear on the bottom of the plastic container. Hold the plastic container away from you and open the valve to release the vapor pressure. These vapors can be very dangerous if inhaled, so keep the end of the container an arm's length away from your face shield as you release the vapors. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a0/Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet2-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet2-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a0/Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet2-Version-2.jpg/v4-760px-Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet2-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":346,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":571.0439560439561,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Release the vapors about every 20 seconds until the potassium hydroxide is completely dissolved. You can tell by looking at the bottom of the container. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/ba/Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/ba/Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Once dissolved, you can add this “methoxide” to the oil in your processor. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a6/Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a6/Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Mix-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
